# batch-pr-rebase-workflow — Version History

## v2.19.0 (2026-06-02)

**Changed by:** HomericIntelligence multi-repo ecosystem PR-drain session (Agamemnon, ProjectOdyssey, ProjectHephaestus, ProjectHermes, AchaeanFleet)
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Bumped version 2.18.0 → 2.19.0 (MINOR — appended new triggers, no behavioral change to existing guidance)
- Added description items (60)-(65):
  - (60) Dependabot refuses `@dependabot rebase` once a non-Dependabot actor commits to the bot PR branch ('edited by someone other than Dependabot') — use `@dependabot recreate` or rebase manually; don't let automation commit to bot PRs
  - (61) a PR is permanently BLOCKED while MERGEABLE with ZERO check-runs/statuses on its head SHA — required named contexts never ran because the workflow never triggered (paused/skipped at PR-open, or a `paths:` filter); push an empty signed commit to re-trigger, or fix the workflow `paths:`
  - (62) 'needs author fix' lint/syntax failures are usually mechanical — read the error (e.g. Mojo's deprecated variadic `List[Type](args)` → typed list literal); reserve real 'needs author' for domain decisions you lack
  - (63) a pip-audit transitive-CVE that reds every PR is fixed by an explicit `pixi.toml` pin (not `--ignore-vuln`), shipped as a separate small PR that unblocks the whole repo
  - (64) a CLEAN, un-armed PR just needs `gh pr merge <n> --auto --squash`
  - (65) a self-inflicted lint-failing artifact on a bot branch is removable directly via a detached worktree + force-with-lease push
- Added matching "When to Use" narrative bullets for each of (60)-(65)
- Added 6 new "Failed Attempts" rows (one per learning) with the concrete recovery command
- Added a Verified On row for the HomericIntelligence ecosystem drain (Agamemnon #422, ProjectHephaestus #881/#879, Hermes #645/#648, AchaeanFleet #690)
- Added frontmatter tags: `dependabot-recreate`, `required-checks-never-ran`, `transitive-cve-pin`, `mechanical-not-author`

### Why

A real cross-repo PR-drain surfaced six recurring blockers that the prior versions didn't cover:
Dependabot's refusal to rebase agent-edited PRs (recover with `recreate`); the BLOCKED-but-MERGEABLE
trap where required checks never ran at all (fix by re-triggering with an empty signed commit, or
correcting a `paths:` filter); the lesson that 'needs author fix' lint failures are usually mechanical
and self-fixable once you read the actual error; the correct fix for a transitive-dep CVE failing
pip-audit (an explicit version pin in pixi.toml shipped as a fast standalone unblock-PR, not the
ignore-list); arming CLEAN-but-un-armed PRs directly; and removing a self-inflicted lint-failing
artifact from a bot branch via a detached worktree. All prior content is unchanged — this revision
only appends the new triggers, bullets, failed-attempt rows, and a Verified On entry.

## v2.18.0 (2026-06-02)

**Changed by:** ProjectNestor serial merge train session (8 sibling feature PRs sharing hot files)
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Bumped version 2.17.0 → 2.18.0
- Added description items (57)-(59): siblings sharing hot files never converge under parallel re-rebase waves — switch to a strict SERIAL MERGE TRAIN; order the train simplest-footprint-first / widest-footprint-last; never block the train on one hard car (flag NEEDS-AUTHOR / RED-OWN-TESTS and move on)
- Added 2 new "Failed Attempts" rows: parallel rebase of 6 hot-file-sharing siblings that all re-conflicted the instant the first merged; repeated parallel re-rebase waves on a diminishing-but-never-converging subset
- Extended the Verified Workflow with a "Serial Merge Train (when PRs share hot files)" subsection: rebase one → push signed → WAIT for MERGE → fetch fresh main → rebase next; simplest-first ordering rule
- Added Verified On row for ProjectNestor (PRs #83/#87/#94/#97/#99/#101 all merged via the serial train, main green at 56d3ec8)

### Why

8 ProjectNestor feature PRs all touched the same hot files (`src/routes.cpp`, `CMakeLists.txt`,
`test/CMakeLists.txt`, `src/store.cpp`, `src/server_main.cpp`, `test/src/test_*.cpp`). We first
rebased them all in PARALLEL onto main `caaa863` (6 went REBASED-CLEAN/BLOCKED). The moment the
first one (#87) merged, main advanced and ALL the other already-rebased PRs went DIRTY/CONFLICTING
again — because they all touch the files #87 just changed. Re-running parallel re-rebase waves
just repeats the churn: whichever merges first re-conflicts the rest, so the wave never converges.

The cure is a strict serial train: process the remaining PRs one at a time — rebase PR onto current
origin/main → push signed → poll `gh pr view <n> --json state` until `state==MERGED` → `git fetch
origin` so main is fresh → only then rebase the next PR. Each car rebases against a main that already
contains every prior merge, so there is zero re-conflict churn. Order simplest-footprint-first,
widest-footprint-last. Never stall the train on one hard PR: flag it (NEEDS-AUTHOR / RED-OWN-TESTS)
and move to the next car.

This sharpens items (52)/(53): waves converge ONLY for DISJOINT-file PRs; when siblings share hot
files, stop doing waves and switch to a serial merge train immediately.

### Previous snapshot (v2.17.0)

