# batch-pr-rebase-workflow — Version History

## v2.17.0 (2026-05-28)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PR #645 single-PR remediation session
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed

- Bumped version 2.16.0 → 2.17.0
- Added description items (55) and (56): duplicate swarm PR silent-drop pattern; pr-policy auto-merge-only failure diagnosis
- Added 2 new "When to Use" bullet points for: Myrmidon duplicate PR race condition; pr-policy failing only on auto-merge
- Added 2 new "Failed Attempts" rows: rebasing a duplicate swarm PR instead of closing it; diagnosing pr-policy without reading job logs

### Why

PR #645 was a duplicate of PR #642 — both generated by Myrmidon agents for issue #625
(docs/README.md consolidation). PR #642 merged ~90 seconds before PR #645's agent checked
in. The rebase silently dropped the commit with "skipped previously applied commit".

The pr-policy check was failing only because auto-merge was not enabled (body had correct
`Closes #625` line; commits were GPG-signed and verified). Reading the actual job log
would have revealed this immediately without a rebase attempt.

Resolution: closed PR #645 with `gh pr close 645 --comment "Superseded: ..."`.

---

## v2.15.0 (2026-05-07)

**Changed by:** ProjectHermes 31-PR rebase swarm session (issue cluster from #422-#597)
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Added 6 new "When to Use" trigger conditions covering: tier-by-complexity ordering, strict-subset PR pair handling, pre-flight Opus triage, design-collision detection, mid-flight hotfix two-pass rebase, cascade churn waves
- Added 3 new "Failed Attempts" rows: sub-agent content corruption (PR #452 case), trusted "already-clean" report when main itself was broken, silently picking auth scheme on design collision
- Added "Step 0.7: Pre-Flight — Triage and Verify Main Green" with 5-item checklist
- Added "Step N: Verify Each Sub-Agent's Output Before Trusting 'Pushed' Reports" with copy-paste verification snippet

### Why

A 46-PR rebase swarm session in HomericIntelligence/ProjectHermes hit several patterns the
existing skill didn't fully document:

1. The session discovered a hidden broken-main (PR #593 had merged with stale pixi.lock that
   broke `pixi install --locked` on every CI run). The fix was a 1-line hotfix PR (#599),
   but it required ALL 17 already-rebased PRs to re-rebase to inherit the new lock — a "two-pass
   wave" pattern not yet codified.
2. A Haiku agent on PR #452 (config DI refactor) produced a force-pushed commit whose content
   was actually PR #555's (Docker pip pinning) — the agent's conflict resolution silently
   pulled in the wrong commit's content. Caught only by post-hoc `git diff --stat` inspection
   before merge. The new "trust but verify" step makes this explicit.
3. Two design-collision pairs landed: #517 vs #576 (auth scheme: X-Dead-Letter-Key vs Bearer)
   and #508 vs #555 (Docker pip pinning: tomllib extraction vs requirements.txt sync). An
   Opus agent correctly aborted #576's rebase on the auth collision; another Opus correctly
   closed #555 as superseded after analyzing the diff. Both outcomes were correct because the
   agents were instructed to escalate design collisions rather than pick.
4. Tier-by-complexity merge ordering (smallest first) drained 31 PRs with only 2 re-rebase
   waves needed. Processing largest first would have caused much more cascade churn.

Final session metrics: 46 open PRs → 14 (+ remaining 14 cascading naturally); 31 merged + 9
closed-superseded; ~30 agents deployed across 8 waves; 0 production breakage.

### Previous version (v2.14.0) snapshot

