## v2.7.0 (2026-04-24)

**Changed by:** ProjectHermes /learn session — mergeStateStatus reference table, silent-drop check in Quick Reference, at-scale issue triage commands, Sonnet vs Haiku agent guidance
**Verification:** verified-ci (confirmed on HomericIntelligence/ProjectHermes with ~30 PRs)

### What changed
- Added `mergeStateStatus` reference table in Phase 1 (CLEAN/DIRTY/CONFLICTING/BLOCKED/UNKNOWN values, meanings, and actions)
- Added one-liner `--jq` command for quick PR state scan
- Added silent-drop rebase check to Quick Reference with explicit CRITICAL annotation
- Added force-push clears auto-merge CRITICAL note to Quick Reference
- Expanded Phase 3.5 model tier selection: Sonnet is **required** for source-code conflicts (not just "escalate"); added explicit guidance on when to spawn parallel Sonnet agents instead of Haiku
- Expanded Phase 13 with at-scale issue triage: bulk fetch via `gh issue list --json`, grep src/ + git log pattern, `gh issue close` with SHA evidence

### Why
The /learn workflow captured six core learnings from a ProjectHermes session with ~30 PRs:
(1) Silent-drop rebase check (`git log origin/main..HEAD --oneline`) belongs in Quick Reference as a required post-rebase step — empty output means the branch was subsumed and the PR should be closed, not force-pushed.
(2) Force-push clears GitHub auto-merge is a critical pattern that causes PRs to stall indefinitely; it was buried in Phase 2 but belongs in the Quick Reference for discoverability.
(3) PRs go DIRTY again after each wave was already documented in Phase 14 but the Quick Reference didn't include the one-liner scan command.
(4) mergeStateStatus values (CLEAN/DIRTY/BLOCKED/UNKNOWN) were documented inline in Phase 1 bullets but lacked a quick-reference table for scanning during a session.
(5) Sonnet agents are preferred over Haiku when PRs have source-code conflicts — Haiku blindly takes --ours; Sonnet understands context. Phase 3.5 now makes this distinction explicit.
(6) Issue triage at scale (~100 issues) benefits from bulk fetch + grep src/ + git log pattern rather than per-issue manual inspection.

### Previous version (v2.6.0) snapshot

(see v2.6.0 entry below)

